items.title: Consent

items.content:
Summary: We investigate how people learn to interact with a fictitious person ("chatbot") using a narrow set of options (emoji icons). The study consists of learning and test phases followed by a short questionnaire.

Purpose: This research looks at how people can use their past experiences to better understand, explain, and control their surroundings. 

Procedures: The study takes about 15 minutes. You will be learning to communicate with Chatbot with a set of emoji icons (like this one: 👍). First, you will become acquainted with the chatbot to get a feel for how it reacts to various messages. Then we will ask you a series of questions to see if you can predict, control, and explain its reactions.

Participant Requirements: Participants in this study must be fluent English speakers aged 18 to 47. Normal vision or glasses/contacts are required. 

Risks: Participating in this study carries no additional risks or discomfort beyond what is typically encountered in day-to-day life or other online activities. 

Benefits: Your participation in the study may provide no personal benefit, but the knowledge gained may be of value to humanity.

Compensation & Costs: You will get a $2 compensation for your time and effort. You may also get a bonus of up to $3 based on how well you complete the task. Costs: none.

Voluntary Participation: Your participation in this research is voluntary.  You may discontinue participation at any time during the research activity.  

Future Use of Information: After removing all identifiable information from your data, we may use it for future research studies or distribute it to other researchers. We would do this without getting additional informed consent from you (or your legally authorized representative).  Sharing of data with other researchers will only be done in such a manner that you will not be identified.

Your IP address will not be captured. By participating in this research, you understand and agree that Carnegie Mellon may be required to disclose your consent form, data and other personally identifiable information as required by law, regulation, subpoena or court order. Otherwise, your confidentiality will be maintained in the following manner: By participating, you understand and agree that the data and information gathered during this study may be used by Carnegie Mellon and published and/or disclosed by Carnegie Mellon to others outside of Carnegie Mellon. However, your name, address, contact information and other direct personal identifiers will not be mentioned in any such publication or dissemination of the research data and/or results by Carnegie Mellon. Note that per regulation all research data must be kept for a minimum of 3 years.
items.title: Confidentiality
Right to Ask Questions & Contact Information:
items.content:
If you have any questions about this study, you should feel free to ask them by contacting the Principal Investigator now at Professor Simon DeDeo, Social and Decision Sciences, 5000 Forbes Avenue, Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, PA 15213; 412-268-3009; sdedeo@andrew.cmu.edu. If you have questions later, desire additional information, or wish to withdraw your participation please contact the Principal Investigator by mail, phone or e-mail in accordance with the contact information listed above.

If you have questions pertaining to your rights as a research participant; or to report concerns to this study, you should contact the Office of Research integrity and Compliance at Carnegie Mellon University. 
Email: irb-review@andrew.cmu.edu. Phone: 412-268-4721.

You may print a copy of this consent form for your records.

items.title: Interaction with a chatbot with emoji
items.content:
This research looks at how people use their past experiences to better understand, explain, and control their surroundings.

It is a game-like study. You will be learning to communicate with a “chatbot” using a fixed set of emoji icons (like this one: 😊). First, you will get acquainted with the chatbot to get a sense of how it responds to various messages. Then, we will ask you a series of questions to see if you can predict, control, and explain the reactions of the chatbot.

The study takes about 15 minutes. Participation is voluntary.

You will get a $2 compensation for your time and effort. You may also get a bonus of up to $3 based on how well you complete the task.

Click the Continue → button below to proceed.

items.title: Test phase: Prediction task
items.content:
In this group of questions, you'll be predicting the reaction of the chatbot based on the conversation history.

You'll get a $0.10 bonus for each correct answer.

Your results will be shown on the final screen of the study.

Click the Begin the task → button to start.

content.text:
Please, do not use any external tools or help of other people.

Rely only your own mind to complete this task.

We'll give you feedback on your results after you finish the study.

Are you ready to start? 

Your first task is just to freely interact with the chatbot 
to get a sense of how it responds to different messages
Press "Enter" to begin the Learning phase

items.title: You've completed the Learning phase!
items.content:
The next part consists of three groups of 10 questions each.

You'll see conversation episodes with corresponding questions. Answer the questions based on your current understanding of the chatbot.

If you're unsure, trust your gut feelings.

You will have 10 seconds to answer each question.

Click the Continue → button below to proceed.

items.title: Test phase: Control task
items.content:
In this group of questions, you have to decide what message should be sent to make the chatbot respond in a certain way.

You'll get a $0.10 bonus for each correct answer.

Your results will be shown on the final screen of the study.

Click the Begin the task → button to start.

content.text:
Please, do not use any external tools or help of other people.

Rely only your own mind to complete this task.

We'll give you feedback on your results after you finish the study.

items.title: Test phase: Explanation task
items.content:
In this part, you'd see a conversation episode and have to decide which of your messages caused the chatbot's final reaction (your first message or the second message).

The message that causes a final response need not be the thing that happened just before. For example, it can sometimes be the case that once a certain action is taken, the next action has little or no ability to change the outcome. In this case, the earlier action may have been the cause.

You'll get a $0.10 bonus for each correct answer.

Your results will be shown on the final screen of the study.

Click the Begin the task → button to start.
